If one wanted to encapsulate all the bad things that I raged about after returning home it comes down to two words &quot;:Jane Fonda&quot;.  What a perfect target for my anger.  Someone that was close enough to be seen all the time and yet far enough away that I could not follow through with my feelings.<br>
Most of the passions that follow PTSD like a bag of crap; Jane Fonda and her actions seem to focus it all.  The betrayal that I felt from a prominent movie star (admittedly using her celebrity status) to further a political agenda; still today remains.  Relflection on her actions now seem a bit self aggrandizing on her part.  Essentially a movie career going nowhere i.e. Barberella, she chooses to get on the front page by sitting on an AA gun in Hanoi.<br>
Person animosity against her?  No, not really.  As I have said before, &quot;Passionate beliefs require passionate actions&quot;.  But was her actions really anti-war?  Or perhaps a shot of getting headlines?  She has said on natoional tv that she had no idea how her actions affected the combat roops.  I don't think so.  I think she knew exactly what she was doing.  I do believe that she made a mistake on judging the long term consequences.
